Dedalus project consists in the upgrade of a classic cartesian 3D printer into a 5DoFs 3D printer. This upgrade helps to overcome the classic limitations of traditional planar FDM, exploiting non-planar printing by compining hobbyist architecture and industrial-grade dynamic stability.
Dedalus stands on 3 fundamental pillars:

Precision: moving beyound open-loop control in favor of a closed-loop system, where position is not assumed but measured thanks to linar encoders;
Decentralization: a control hierarchy that separates high-level kinematic planning (relied to Raspberry Pi5) from low-latency motor management implemented on a STM32H7 (ARM Cortex M7) microcontroller;
Mechanical reliability: linear rails and DC motors designed to perform smooth operations;

An integrated engineering approach led to custom development of all tools: at first, the low-level control board is designed from the ground up, as well the bare-metal firmware. By exploiting the microcontroller features, it is possible to separate the data acquisition from the CPU computations, in order to achieve a highly reactive control. The motion planning software is custom as well, started from the material developed during the Precision Engineering course teached by prof. Paolo Bosetti at University of Trento. Last but not least, the digital-twin is developed from the ground up as well and integrated with the machine real-world operation by means of the Mechatronic systems simulations: Modeling’s approach teached by prof. Francesco Biral at University of Trento.
